Background

While 828 million people worldwide continue to go to bed hungry, an estimated 10 million hectares of forest are cleared yearly (about 27400 hectares per day). Yet, the conversion of forests into agricultural land does not seem to imply a systematic reduction of hunger worldwide, especially in developing countries. Alternatively, one can dare to hope for innovations aimed at reconverting degraded land into arable land or, better still, into forests, a better approach to fighting food insecurity.

As part of my doctoral research, I am seeking to better understand which farming systems lead to social sustainability. Social sustainability is concerned with several aspects of human and societal development, among which human well-being very often comes first. Food security is a major component of human well-being (Hammond et al., 2021) often included in agrifood systems’ social sustainability assessments as indicated in my previous paper (Orou Sannou & al, forthcoming ). This study aims to improve our understanding of the causal mechanisms leading to food security, considered as a social sustainability aspect. It estimates the effect of land use and land cover changes (we use this generic term to refer to changes in tree and crop cover) on food security in sub-Saharan African countries with a focus on countries participating in the Great Green Wall (GGW) initiative.

This Rmarkdown file contains the code I developed for the study and will not include extensive interpretations of the results. The draft manuscript is still undergoing some revisions before submission to a peer-reviewed journal.

Data

  • Since 2014 FAO conducts the Food Insecurity Experience Scale (FIES) survey in several countries across the world. This standardized survey helps to produce cross-country comparable food insecurity prevalence. Nationally representative food insecurity prevalence will be used as the dependent variable in this study.

  • A mere combination of trees and crops is considered as a type of multifunctional land use. As such, using Dynamic World data (Brown et al., 2022), the percentage of tree and crop cover in the total area of selected countries will be used in an attempt to capture the effect of multifunctional land use on food security in this study.

  • However, in order to improve the internal validity of the estimated parameters and to limit the effect of external confounding factors, we will control for other key aspects that could affect an individual’s food security such as education level, health status, living conditions and climatic factors such as agricultural drought and political factors such as governance effectiveness.

  • UNDP defines the Human Development Index (HDI) as a summary measure of achievement in key dimensions of human development including the distribution of education, health and living standards. It will serve as a control variable in this study.

  • Agricultural Drought Indicator: the six-month Standardized Precipitation Index (SPI-6) was used by Dasgupta and Robinson (2022) as a measure of agricultural drought. Our model considered a specification with annual mean SPI-06 and another with the Risk of Drought Impact for Agriculture Index (RDrI-Agri) which is a more robust indicator for agricultural drought that combines drought hazard, drought exposure and drought vulnerability aspects. The raster datasets were obtained from the Global Drought Observatory.

  • Governance Effectiveness: Government effectiveness is a World Bank indicator that captures perceptions of the quality of many aspects of public services in a country such as the quality of the civil service and the degree of its independence from political pressures, the quality of policy formulation and implementation, and the credibility of the government’s commitment to such policies.

Writting a Function for globally equated prevalence calculation

I have written a function called fies.prev that computes food insecurity prevalence at country level and uses the global standard to equate the obtained rates following the Rasch Model approach as described in detail by FAO. For more information visit this website. The function is saved as Fies Prevalence in the R project folder and can be accessed using source(“Fies Prevalence”).

 fies.prev <- function(data, year, country) {
  
 
  
  # The 2021 FIES dataset structure seems to differ from previous waves. Therefore, I start with
  # an if statement to handle the selection of corresponding columns
  
  if (colnames(data[ ,1]) == "Random_ID"){
     XX.data  <-  data[,2:9]
  } else {
    XX.data  <-  data[,1:8]
  }
  
  # Making sure all variables are coded as numeric
  XX.data  <-  data.frame(lapply(XX.data, as.numeric))
  
  # Saving FIES corresponding weights
  wt.data  <-  data$wt
  
  # Calculating raw scores (number of yes for each individual to the 8 questions)
  rv.data <- rowSums(XX.data)

  # Number of items (questions) of the FIES
  k <- ncol(XX.data)
  
  # Rash Model
  rr.data <- RM.w(XX.data, wt.data)
  
  # Pre-defined thresholds on the latent trait
  # sthresh contains two possible thresholds on the latent trait
  #sthresh <- c(-0.25, 1.81)
  
  #pp.data <- prob.assign(rr.data, sthres = sthresh)$sprob
  
  
  # VoH 2014-2015 global standard
  #b.tot <- c(-1.2590036, -0.8991436, -1.0876362,  0.4163556, -0.2506451,  0.4466926,  0.8065710, 1.8268093)
  
  # Equating of country 1 to the global standard
  ee <- equating.fun(rr.data, tol=0.5)

  # Equated prevalence rates
  prev <- ee$prevs*100

  # Correlation between common items
  cor <- ee$cor.comm.items
  
  
  # Dataframe of the prevalence rates and correlation
  results <- as.data.frame(cbind(prev, cor))
  
  # convert rownames into a new column nammed "measure"
  results$measure <- row.names(results) 
  
  # remove the rownames
  rownames(results) <- NULL
  
  # create a "year" variable that will use the year argument provided in the function 
  results$year <-  year
  
  # create a "country" variable that will use the country argument provided in the function 
  results$country <- country
  
  # round results to two decimals
  results$prev <- round(results$prev, 2)
  
  results$cor <- round(results$cor, 2)
  #reorder the columns
  results <- dplyr::select(results, "country", "measure", "year", "prev", "cor")
  
  return(results)

}

naggw.list <- list.files("naggw_fies", pattern="*.dta",
                       full.names = TRUE)



naggw.df <- data.frame(matrix(ncol = 5, nrow = 0)) 



for (i in 1:length(naggw.list)) {
  
  #extracting country's short name
  country <- substr(basename(naggw.list[i]),1, 
                 nchar(basename(naggw.list[i]))-33)
  
  #extracting year of data
  year <- substr(basename(naggw.list[i]),5, 
                 nchar(basename(naggw.list[i]))-28)
  
  # assign each survey file from the list to an object called dta.file
  dta.file <- naggw.list[i]
  
  # reading the raw fies survey data
  fies.data <- haven::read_dta(dta.file)
  
  # country prevalence calculation
  country_prev <- fies.prev(fies.data, year, country)
  
  # saving all countries prevalence in one dataframe
  naggw.df <- rbind(naggw.df, country_prev)
  
  
  
}

Dynamic World : A near realtime land cover dataset

Dynamic World time series were retrieved on Google Earth Engine using the python package geemap.
Based on dynamic world time series, the area for each land cover class was computed for each country. I considered the country borders provided by FAO’s 2015 Global Administrative Unit Layers. The python code used for area calculations is saved as “Land_cover_areas_calculations” and can be found in the project folder. For each country, we consider the crop calendars provided by USDA to select the most appropriate months to extract land cover classification time series. This helps to lower the risk of calculating land classes that will be biased for the “crops” class.

#import LULC data derived from Dynamic World Land Cover data on GEE

Agricultural Drought Indicators

The Standardized Precipitation Index (SPI)

SPI is is a statistical index comparing the total precipitation received at a particular location during a period of n months with the long-term precipitation distribution for the same period of time at that location (reference period is 1981-2010). Monthly accumulation periods (n) are 1, 3, 6, 9, 12, 24 or 48 months. The corresponding SPIs are denoted as SPI-1, SPI-3, SPI-6, etc. We use the SPI-6 in this study.

# import spi files from 2014 to 2020

The Risk of Drought Impacts for Agriculture (RDrI-Agri)

The Risk of Drought Impact for Agriculture (RDrI-Agri) is a robust indicator that combines drought hazard, drought exposure and drought vulnerability aspects. The drought hazard component is calculated by integrating three main drought indicators: the Standardized Precipitation Index (SPI), the Soil Moisture Anomaly (SMA), the FAPAR Anomaly. The drought exposure component integrates four indicators including the population, agricultural lands, livestock and water stress. Drought vulnerability is calculated as the propensity of exposed elements to suffer adverse effects when impacted by a drought event. I will import raster files of RDrI-Agri and extract the mean RDrI-Agri of the study locations.

Write “spi.extr” function to extract the SPI stats

spi.extr <- function(shp.file, spi.file,  stat, 
                      spi.country) {
  
  #ensure shpfile projection matches with spifile projection
  projected <- sp::spTransform(shp.file, CRS = crs(spi.file))
  
  # clip spifile to country borders
  spi_clip <- terra::crop(spi.file, projected, snap = "out")
  
  # create a raster stack from the clipped country spi
  stack <- raster::stack(spi_clip)
  
  # mask values 
  masked <- terra::mask(stack, projected)
  
  # compute stats and format as dataframe with more 
  # intuitive rowmanes
  stat <- data.frame(raster::cellStats(masked, stat = stat),
                     row.names = c("SPI06-Jan","SPI06-Feb",
                                   "SPI06-Mar", "SPI06-Apr",
                                   "SPI06-May", "SPI06-Jun",
                                   "SPI06-Jul", "SPI06-Aug",
                                   "SPI06-Sep", "SPI06-Oct",
                                   "SPI06-Nov", "SPI06-Dec"))
  
  # rownames to a new column
  stat$month <- row.names(stat)
  # drop rownames
  row.names(stat) <- NULL
  # rename values column
  names(stat)[1] ="value"
  # round value to 4 decimal points
  stat$value <- round(stat$value, 4)
  # assign year
  #stat$year <- spi.year
  #assign country name
  stat$country <- spi.country
  # reorder columns
  stat <- stat[, c(3, 2, 1)]
  #stat <- dplyr::select(stat, "country",  "month", "value")
  return(stat)

}

Write “rdri.extr” function to extract the RDrI stats

rdri.extr <- function(shp.file, rdri.file,  stat, 
                      rdri.country) {
  
  #ensure shpfile projection matches with spifile projection
  projected <- sp::spTransform(shp.file, CRS = crs(rdri.file))
  
  # clip spifile to country borders
  rdri_clip <- terra::crop(rdri.file, projected, snap = "out")
  
  # create a raster stack from the clipped country spi
  stack <- raster::stack(rdri_clip)
  
  # mask values 
  masked <- terra::mask(stack, projected)
  
  # compute stats and format as dataframe with more 
  # intuitive rowmanes
  stat <- data.frame(raster::cellStats(masked, stat = stat),
                     row.names = c("rdria_1","rdria_2", "rdria_3", "rdria_4",
                                   "rdria_5","rdria_6", "rdria_7", "rdria_8",
                                   "rdria_9","rdria_10", "rdria_11", "rdria_12",
                                   "rdria_13","rdria_14", "rdria_15", "rdria_16",
                                   "rdria_17","rdria_18", "rdria_19", "rdria_20",
                                   "rdria_21","rdria_22", "rdria_23", "rdria_24",
                                   "rdria_25","rdria_26", "rdria_27", "rdria_28",
                                   "rdria_29","rdria_30", "rdria_31", "rdria_32",
                                   "rdria_33","rdria_34", "rdria_35", "rdria_36"))
  
  # rownames to a new column
  stat$period <- row.names(stat)
  # drop rownames
  row.names(stat) <- NULL
  # rename values column
  names(stat)[1] ="value"
  # round value to 4 decimal points
  stat$value <- round(stat$value, 2)
  # assign year
  #stat$year <- spi.year
  #assign country name
  stat$country <- rdri.country
  # reorder columns
  stat <- stat[, c(3, 2, 1)]
  #stat <- dplyr::select(stat, "country",  "month", "value")
  return(stat)
  
}

Balancing the obtained panel data by imputing remaining missing cells

In its current structure, the obtained panel data is unbalanced. This might lead to inconsistent and biased parameter estimations. FIES was not conducted in some countries strating from 2020. Therefore, I will remove the years 2020 and 2021 as some countries do not have data for those years. Then I will impute the remaining mising cells of food insecurity prevalence in Niger by replacing it with the country mean. This will help have a balanced panel.

blc_panel <- panel %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% # to consider mean value of target country only
  mutate_at(vars(FI_mod, FI_sev), 
            ~replace_na(.,mean(., na.rm = TRUE))) %>% #replace missing FI_mod and FI_sev by mean
  ungroup()

The Welch t-test performed for moderate FI and the classical t-test performed for severe FI confirm a significant difference of means of moderate and severe FI between GGW countries and not GGW countries.

Can we attribute the observed lower average moderate FI and severe FI in GGW countries compared to other African countries not part of the initiative to the GGW-induced land use and land cover change? The panel data regression can help test this hypothesis.

              index = c("country", "year"), # c(group index, time index)
              model = "pooling")

The parameters for “hdi” and “crops”, are significant. According to Wooldridge (2010), the pooled ols can not be used here as we are observing the same sample of countries along different period of time. However, the f-test which compares the model with zero predictor variables (the intercept only model), and decides whether added coefficients improved the model. In this case the result is significant, therefore, the coefficients included in the model did improve the model’s fit.

Hausman test for fixed versus random effects

The Hausman test is used to decide whether to use fixed effects or random effects.

  • H0: FE coefficients are not significantly different from the RE coefficients

  • Ha: FE coefficients are significantly different from the RE coefficients

# If the Hausman test statistic is significant, use FE estimator because it is consistent

The Hausman Test statistic is significant. Therefore the Fixed Effect estimator could be a better option.

However, none of the estimated fixed effect parameters is significant although its F-statistic is. According to Wooldridge (2010), in chapters 13 and 14, it is important to include dummy variables for each studied year that are being observed as the effects of time are really strong.

I am trying the time-varying FE estimator to see if I get any meaningful results.

For relatively constant predictors or those that change slowly over time, the fixed effect specification tends to produce odd estimates since the specification is used precisely to control for factors that do not vary over time (Beck, 2001; Lenaerts and Demont, 2021). The argument is particularly valid for geography-related variables, such as the predictor variables of interest in this study (land use and land cover) which are known to be slow changing variables. Therefore I am choosing a pooled OLS with time dummies.

Pooled OLS with time dummies

I ran a simple time invariance test for each independent variable with country dummies. High R^2 suggest that the variable do not vary much across countries and therefore its effect can will not be captured by a fixed effect specification.
